Fredericton Transit Ridership Analysis¶

This notebook presents a detailed analysis of the Fredericton Transit Data using data from 2019-2023. The analysis is divided into the following sections:

  1. Data Pre-processing(already done through external scripts)
  2. Weather Impact Analysis on Transit Ridership
  3. Clustering of Transit Users

Importing the Pre-processed Enriched Transit-Weather Dataset¶

  • The dataset used is a consolidated/combined dataset that consists of both the Fredericton Transit Data from the Hotspot Transit App and the Weather Data from a National Meteorological Service.
  • The consolidated dataset was then processed using external scripts and saved as a CSV file. The following actions were performed during the pre-processing:
    1. Cleaning the data by removing duplicates and missing values, removing spurious transit sessions and outliers that do not conform to the bus schedules.
    2. Enriching the data by adding new columns such as the day of the week, the month, the hour of the day, and pertinent weather conditions.
    3. Algorithmically determining and assigning the Boarding Stop for each of the transit sessions, through the use of the Official Fredericton Transit Schedule, bus route and boarding time.

The Transit Usage Trend plot shows the following insights:

  • The ridership starts to recover in the year 2021, indicating a return to normalcy.
  • There seems to be a sharp increase in September of both 2021 and 2022, which could be due to the start of the academic year, as students return to school and university.
  • The levels of transit ridership has increased drastically in 2022 compared to 2021, indicating a positive trend in the usage of the transit service. How much of this increase is due to the return to normalcy post-pandemic and how much is due to other factors is yet to be determined.
  • The ridership trends seem to be coinciding with the number of unique transit users, indicating that the increase in transit sessions is due to an increase in the number of unique users. This also implies that the existing users are not varying their usage patterns significantly over

Bus-Stop Usage Analysis¶

  • The bus-stop usage analysis is performed to understand the popularity of the different bus stops among the transit users.
  • This can lead to targeted improvements in the infrastructure and services provided at the most popular bus stops.
  • King's Place and Regent Mall are the hubs at which most of the transit users board the buses. These are at downtown and uptown locations, respectively, and are likely to be the most popular boarding points due to their central locations. But what other places could be made hubs to increase the convenience of the transit service?
In [4]:
# Calculate the number of times each bus stop was used by the transit users
bus_stop_usage = data[CONSTANTS.SESSION_ID].groupby(data['boarding_stop']).count().sort_values(ascending=False)
# Filter any bus stops with the lowest 50% of usage, as this increases the readability of the plot while retaining the most popular bus stops and therefore the most impactful information
bus_stop_usage = bus_stop_usage[bus_stop_usage > bus_stop_usage.median()].to_dict()
# Plot the Bus-Stop Usage Analysis
UTILITIES.plot_bar_chart(bus_stop_usage, 'Bus-Stop Usage Analysis', 'Bus Stops', 'Number of Transit Sessions')

Apart from King's Place and Regent Mall, the most popular bus stops are:

  • Windsor/Montgomery - This bus stop is located right next to University of New Brunswick(UNB) and is likely to be popular among students. This indicates that the bus service is being used by students to commute to and from the university to a significant extent.
  • Forest Hill/Biggs - This bus stop is located near the student residences and is likely to be popular among students living in that area. This is further evidence of the popularity of the bus service among students.

It is clear that the bus service is being used by students to a significant extent, and this information can be used to make targeted decisions to improve the service for this demographic.

Understanding Transit User Preferences¶

  • The data is pivoted on 3 main attributes, which will help understand the following:
    1. Route - Understanding the most popular routes for each user.
    2. Part of the Day - Understanding the most popular times of the day for each user.
    3. Boarding Stop - Understanding the most popular boarding stops for each user.
  • This will help in understanding the user preferences through the data.
In [5]:
# Calculate the number of times a single user has boarded a bus for each Route,the Part of the Day in which they boarded, and Boarding Stop they used
route_pivoted = pd.crosstab(data['user_id'], data['route'])
part_of_day_pivoted = pd.crosstab(data['user_id'], data['part_of_day'])
boarding_counts = pd.crosstab(data['user_id'], data['boarding_stop'])
# Combine the pivoted dataframes on 'user_id' in a single operation
user_transit_pattern = pd.concat([route_pivoted, part_of_day_pivoted, boarding_counts], axis=1)
# Drop any NaN values in-place
user_transit_pattern.dropna(inplace=True)

Clustering of Transit Users based on their Transit Patterns¶

The data is clustered using the K-Means Clustering Algorithm to group the users based on their transit patterns. This will help in understanding the different user groups and their preferences. And, consequently, help in making targeted decisions to improve the transit service.

Transit Ridership is measured mainly on overall user-base satisfaction, with each user bringing in roughly the same revenue per ride as well as only one class of users existing, unlike an airline. The overall satisfaction of the user base is more important than the satisfaction of individual users. The goal is to increase the number of users and the number of rides per user, which will increase the overall ridership.

Elbow Method to find the optimal number of clusters:¶

  • The Elbow Method calculates the sum of squared distances between the data points and their assigned clusters' centroids for different values of K.
  • A Silhouette Score is calculated for each K, which is a measure of how similar an object is to its cluster compared to other clusters.
  • The K with the highest Silhouette Score is considered the optimal number of clusters.
In [6]:
# Finding the best random state and cluster number
best_kmeans = None
best_k = None
silhouette_scores = {}
cluster_range = range(5, 15)
for k in cluster_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=CONSTANTS.RANDOM_SEED)
    kmeans.fit(user_transit_pattern)
    silhouette_score = metrics.silhouette_score(user_transit_pattern, kmeans.labels_)
    silhouette_scores[k] = silhouette_score
# Find the best cluster number
best_k = max(silhouette_scores, key=silhouette_scores.get)
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 6))
plt.plot(silhouette_scores.keys(), silhouette_scores.values(), marker='o')
# Annotate the best cluster number
plt.annotate(f'Best Cluster Number: {best_k}', xy=(best_k, silhouette_scores[best_k]),
             xytext=(best_k, silhouette_scores[best_k]),
             arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.5))
plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal Number of Clusters')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')
plt.show()

Fit the Best K-Means Model and Assign Cluster Labels to the Users¶

  • The best K-Means model is fitted using the optimal number of clusters obtained from the Elbow Method.
  • The cluster labels are then assigned to the users based on this model.
In [7]:
kmeans_clustering_model = KMeans(n_clusters=best_k
                 , random_state=CONSTANTS.RANDOM_SEED)
kmeans_clustering_model.fit(user_transit_pattern)
cluster_labels = kmeans_clustering_model.labels_
user_transit_pattern['Cluster'] = cluster_labels

Inter-Day Bus Usage of the Cluster-Specific Users¶

  • The inter-day bus usage of the cluster-specific users is calculated to understand the hourly bus usage of the users for each day of the week.
  • Per-day bus usage is useful in understanding the daily patterns of the users. And, has the necessary level of granularity to make targeted decisions about the bus schedules.
In [11]:
# Find the Inter-Day Bus Usage of the Cluster-Specific Users
cluster_specific_users = data[data['user_id'].isin(cluster_specific_user_transit_pattern.index)]
# Calculate the hourly bus usage of the cluster-specific users for each day of the week
hourly_bus_usage = cluster_specific_users.groupby([cluster_specific_users[CONSTANTS.START_TIME].dt.hour, 'day_of_week'])['session_id'].count().unstack()
# Find the mean line that is the average hourly bus usage of the cluster-specific user for all days of the week
hourly_bus_usage['all_days'] = hourly_bus_usage.mean(axis=1)
# Plotting the hourly bus usage of the cluster-specific users
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(18, 6))
hourly_bus_usage.drop('all_days', axis=1).plot(ax=ax, colormap='viridis', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)
hourly_bus_usage['all_days'].plot(ax=ax, color='black', linestyle='solid', label='All Days', linewidth=2)
ax.set_xlabel('Hour of the Day(in 24-Hour Format)')
ax.set_ylabel('Number of Transit Sessions')
ax.set_title('Inter-Day Bus Usage of the Cluster-Specific Users')
ax.legend(title='Day of the Week')
plt.show()

Inference of the Inter-Day Bus Usage of the Cluster-Specific Users¶

There are 2 peaks in the hourly bus usage of the cluster-specific users, around 8 AM and 5 PM. This indicates that the users are likely to be commuting to and from work. The hourly bus usage is relatively low during the rest of the day, indicating that the users are not using the bus service for other purposes. This information can be used to optimize the bus schedules to cater to the peak hours and improve the overall user experience.

Weather Impact Analysis on Transit Ridership¶

  • The impact of weather on transit ridership is analyzed to understand the effect of weather conditions on the number of transit sessions.
  • The analysis is performed by calculating the average total sessions daily with and without precipitation on weekdays and weekends.
In [12]:
# Create a column that indicates whether it rained or snowed on a particular day, in essence, if it precipitated
data['precipitation'] = pd.Series(['Precipitation' if (x+y) > 0 else 'No Precipitation' for x, y in zip(data['rain'], data['snow'])])
data['weekend'] = data['day_of_week'].apply(lambda x: "Weekend" if x in ['Saturday','Sunday'] else "Weekday")
# Calculate the average total sessions daily with and without precipitation on weekdays and weekends
agg_data = data.groupby(['weekend', 'precipitation'])['session_id'].count().unstack()
UTILITIES.plot_grouped_bar_chart(agg_data, 'Average Total Sessions Daily with and without Precipitation on Weekdays and Weekends', 'Precipitation', 'Number of Transit Sessions')

The weather impact analysis gives us a clear understanding of the effect of weather conditions on the number of transit sessions. The analysis provides the following inferences:

  • Precipitation has a noticeable negative impact on transit sessions on both weekdays and weekends, with a more pronounced effect during the weekend.
  • The sharp decrease in ridership on rainy days could be partly mitigated through proactive communication strategies. Informing riders about anticipated service adjustments and providing weatherproof amenities might improve user experience and maintain higher ridership levels during undesirable weather conditions.
  • The magnitude of decrease of transit ridership on days with precipitation is drastically higher on weekends than on weekdays. This could be due to the fact that people prefer to stay indoors on weekends when the weather is not favorable, if the activities they had planned are not urgent or mandatory unlike weekdays.

Conclusion¶

The analysis of the Fredericton Transit Data has provided valuable insights into the transit ridership patterns, user preferences, and the impact of weather conditions on transit ridership. The key takeaways from the analysis are as follows:

  • The transit ridership has shown a positive trend over the years, with a noticeable increase in Fall, which could be attributed to the start of the academic year. Increasing frequency and capacity during these peak times could help in accommodating the increased ridership.
  • Students are a significant user group of the transit service, with popular boarding stops near the University of New Brunswick and student residences. Improving the service for this demographic could lead to increased ridership and higher number of satisfied users.
  • Adverse weather conditions, especially precipitation, have a negative impact on transit ridership, with a more pronounced effect on weekends. Proactive communication strategies and weatherproof amenities could help in maintaining higher ridership levels during unfavorable weather conditions.
